posts.name: Zach Hoegberg
posts.cooked:
I have no advice to offer on the specifics of casting. However, I do have some general advice on the topic: make sure you think hard about why you are pursuing this and what you hope to gain. If the why is “learning” and the what you hope to gain is “student exposure to a new manufacturing process,” then godspeed and good luck, I wish you all the success in the world.

If you are looking for a strategic advantage, or even worse, then I implore you to reconsider. There is almost certainly no strategic advantage in terms of time or performance over using COTS wheels/rollers as-is or modified as needed; save your time and effort to optimize elsewhere. In terms of cost, between the vacuum setup and other start-up infrastructure, as well as the necessary quantity of pre-season test wheels and iterations, there is no way you will save money, at least for several years. And the performance will most likely not live up to commercially available injection-molded options anyway.

posts.name: Martin L. M.
posts.cooked: We have had success with running casted swerve treads on sds billet wheels, which we replace at each event for more testing, showing minimal wear. Custom-casted wheels on our robot this year offer better options for selecting any size, hardness, colors, etc. Casted star wheels from 5885’s robot and petunia rollers from our 2024 robot, both tested by 9062, have shown great performance. All wheels are casted in urethane.

In terms of cost, between the vacuum setup and other startup infrastructure, Zaque mentions that it is not necessary if you aren’t driving an FRC robot with casted wheels (like those suggested in the original post). The combat robotics program at his school uses a simple 3D mold and silicone for wheels, though he isn’t familiar with the specifics. While time is still a significant investment, the financial investment isn’t too bad.

posts.name: Billfred Leverette (he/him/not Bill)
posts.cooked:
1293 didn’t cast our intake wheels this year but we did print them out of TPU specifically the Polymaker 95A.  

We got deeper into FSC North Charleston we ran into some traction problems. With hindsight we didn’t attempt to clean off the tread surface so I don’t know if that would’ve bailed us out. We used self-fusing silicone tape instead which kept us largely in good shape for the rest of the tournament which was our last one of the season. We’re going to experiment with printing some actual tread on the wheels this off-season.  

What I do know is that it was promising performance at a fraction of what it would’ve cost us to buy COTS compliant wheels.

posts.name: Nick Foote
posts.cooked: We created a mold by cutting out sheets of polycarbonate and bolting them together, which worked well for our needs and allowed easy release from smooth surfaces. We attempted a larger version initially, but it proved too thin and impractical for our purposes. Instead, if we had used a smaller radius and incorporated a 3D-printed hub, it might have been suitable for smaller wheels. However, these were significantly oversized at 11 inches.
